Context: George Brown College has been at the heart of Toronto's East Bayfront urban development since 2012. Notable buildings opened by the college include the Daphne Cockwell Centre for Health Sciences (2012), the first residence, The George (2016), and the School of Design at Daniels Waterfront â€“ City of the Arts (2019). A new addition to the campus is Limberlost Place, a 10-storey mass timber and net zero carbon emissions building, designed by Moriyama & Teshima Architects and Acton Ostry Architects. The building won the Excellence in Design Innovation award at the Waterfront Design Review Panel (WDRP) Awards in 2022. Expected to be completed by September 2024, Limberlost Place will serve as a living lab for students and is designed to harness green energy through solar chimneys and deep-water cooling from Lake Ontario. Currently under construction at the corner of Queens Quay East and Dockside Drive, north of the Daphne Cockwell Centre for Health Sciences, Limberlost Place will welcome students into the building in January 2025.
